# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: skew-heap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:skew-heap/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:skew-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In computer science, a **leftist tree** or **leftist heap** is a priority queue implemented with a variant of a binary heap.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Every node x has an *s-value* which is the distance to the nearest leaf in subtree rooted at x.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In contrast to a *binary heap*, a leftist tree attempts to be very unbalanced.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In addition to the heap property, leftist trees are maintained so the right descendant of each node has the lower s-value.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The height-biased leftist tree was invented by Clark Allan Crane.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The name comes from the fact that the left subtree is usually taller than the right subtree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] When inserting a new node into a tree, a new one-node tree is created and merged into the existing tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] To delete an item, it is replaced by the merge of its left and right sub-trees.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Both these operations take O(log *n*) time.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] For insertions, this is slower than Fibonacci heaps, which support insertion in O(1) (constant) amortized time, and O(log *n*) worst-case.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Leftist trees are advantageous because of their ability to merge quickly, compared to binary heaps which take Θ(*n*).
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In almost all cases, the merging of skew heaps has better performance.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] However merging leftist heaps has worst-case O(log *n*) complexity while merging skew heaps has only amortized O(log *n*) complexity.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The usual leftist tree is a *height-biased* leftist tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] However, other biases can exist, such as in the *weight-biased* leftist tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The exact worst-case complexity of both types of leftist trees is 2 log2 *n*, counting comparisons.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The **s-value** (or **rank**) of a node is the distance from that node to the nearest empty position in the subtree rooted at that node.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Put another way, the s-value of a `null` child is implicitly zero.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Other nodes have an s-value equal to one more the minimum of their children's s-values.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, in the example at right, all nodes with at least one missing child have an s-value of 1, while node 4 has an s-value of 2, since its right child (8) has an s-value of 1.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Knowing the shortest path to the nearest missing leaf in the subtree rooted at *x* is exactly of *s*(*x*), every node at depth *s*(*x*)−1 or less has exactly 2 children since *s*(*x*) would have been less if not.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Meaning that the size of the tree rooted at *x* is at least $2^{s(x)}-1$ .
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, *s*(*x*) is at most $\log {(m+1)}$ , *m* being the number of nodes of the subtree rooted at *x*.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Most operations on a Height Biased Leftist Tree are done using the merge operation.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation takes two Min HBLTs as input and returns a Min HBLT containing all the nodes in the original Min HBLTs put together.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] If either of A or B is empty, the merge returns the other one.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In case of Min HBLTs, assume we have two trees rooted at A and B where A.key $\leq$ B.key.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Otherwise we can swap A and B so that the condition above holds.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The merge is done recursively by merging B with A's right subtree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This might change the S-value of A's right subtree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] To maintain the leftist tree property, after each merge is done, we check if the S-value of right subtree became bigger than the S-value of left subtree during the recursive merge calls.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] If so, we swap the right and left subtrees (If one child is missing, it should be the right one).
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Since we assumed that A's root is greater than B's, the heap property is also maintained.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] An example of how the merge operation in a leftist tree works is depicted.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] When the recursion unwinds, we swap left and right children if x.right.s_value > x.left.s_value for every node x.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In this case we swapped the subtrees rooted at nodes with keys 7 and 10.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Insertion is done using the merge operation.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] An insertion of a node into an already existing Min HBLT, creates a HBLT tree of size one with that node and merges it with the existing tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The Min element in a Min HBLT is the root.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, in order to delete the Min, the root is deleted and its subtrees are merged to form the new Min HBLT.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Initializing a height biased leftist tree is primarily done in one of two ways.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The first is to merge each node one at a time into one HBLT.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This process is inefficient and takes O(*nlogn*) time.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The other approach is to use a queue to store each node and resulting tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The first two items in the queue are removed, merged, and placed back into the queue.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This can initialize a HBLT in O(*n*) time.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This approach is detailed in the three diagrams supplied.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] A min height biased leftist tree is shown.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] To initialize a min HBLT, place each element to be added to the tree into a queue.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In the example (see Part 1 to the left), the set of numbers [4, 8, 10, 9, 1, 3, 5, 6, 11] are initialized.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Each line of the diagram represents another cycle of the algorithm, depicting the contents of the queue.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The first five steps are easy to follow.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Notice that the freshly created HBLT is added to the end of the queue.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In the fifth step, the first occurrence of an s-value greater than 1 occurs.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The sixth step shows two trees merged with each other, with predictable results.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] In part 2 a slightly more complex merge happens.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The tree with the lower value (tree x) has a right child, so merge must be called again on the subtree rooted by tree x's right child and the other tree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] After the merge with the subtree, the resulting tree is put back into tree x.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The s-value of the right child (s=2) is now greater than the s-value of the left child (s=1), so they must be swapped.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The s-value of the root node 4 is also now 2.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Here, we recursively call merge twice (each time with the right child 's subtree that is not grayed out).
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This uses the same process described for part 2.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] If we have a pointer to a node x in a Min HBLT, we can delete it as follows: Replace the node x with the result of merging its two subtrees and update the s-values of the nodes on the path from x to the root, swapping the right and left subtrees if necessary to maintain the leftist tree property.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The upward traversal is continued until either we hit the root or the s-value does not change.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Since we are deleting an element, the S-values on the path traversed cannot be increased.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Every node that is already the right child of its parent and causes its parent's s-value to be decreased, will remain on the right.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Every node that is its parent's left child and causes the parent's s-value to be decreased has to be swapped with its right sibling if the s-value becomes lower than the current s-value of the right child.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Each node needs to have a pointer to its parent, so that we can traverse the path to the root updating the s-values.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] When the traversal ends at some node y, the nodes traversed all lie on the rightmost path rooted at node y.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] It follows that the number of nodes traversed is at most log(m), m being the size of the subtree rooted at y.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, this operation also takes O(lg m) to perform.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Leftist trees can also be weight biased.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] WBLTs ensure w(x.left) ≥ w(x.right) for all internal nodes x.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] WBLT operations ensure this invariant by swapping the children of a node when the right subtree outgrows the left one, just as in HBLT operations.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation in WBLTs can be done using a single top to bottom traversal since the number of nodes in the subtrees are known prior to recursive call to merge.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, we can swap left and right subtrees if the total number of nodes in the right subtree and the tree to be merged is bigger than the number of nodes in the left subtree.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] This allows the operations be completed in a single path and so improves the time complexity of the operations by a constant factor.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation is depicted in the graph below.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Insertions and deletion of the min element can be done in the same as for HBLTs using the merge operation.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] Although WBLTs outperform HBLTs in merge, insertion and deletion of the Min key by a constant factor, the *O*(log *n*) bound is not guaranteed when deleting an arbitrary element from WBLTs, since θ(*n*) nodes have to be traversed.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] If this was an HBLT, then deleting the leaf node with key 60 would take *O*(1) time and updating the s-values is not needed since the length of rightmost path for all the nodes does not change.
[src:skew-heap/leftist-tree] But in an WBLT tree, we have to update the weight of each node back to the root, which takes *O*(*n*) worst case.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] A **pairing heap** is a type of heap data structure with relatively simple implementation and excellent practical amortized performance, introduced by Michael Fredman, Robert Sedgewick, Daniel Sleator, and Robert Tarjan in 1986.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Pairing heaps are heap-ordered multiway tree structures, and can be considered simplified Fibonacci heaps.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The analysis of pairing heaps' time complexity was initially inspired by that of splay trees.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The amortized time per *delete-min* is *O*(log *n*), and the operations *find-min*, *meld*, and *insert* run in *O*(1) time.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] When a *decrease-key* operation is added as well, determining the precise asymptotic running time of pairing heaps has turned out to be difficult.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Initially, the time complexity of this operation was conjectured on empirical grounds to be *O*(1), but Fredman proved that the amortized time per *decrease-key* is at least $\Omega (\log \log n)$ for some sequences of operations.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Using a different amortization argument, Pettie then proved that *insert*, *meld*, and *decrease-key* all run in $O(2^{2{\sqrt {\log \log n}}})$ amortized time, which is $o(\log n)$ .
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Elmasry later introduced elaborations of pairing heaps (lazy, consolidate) for which *decrease-key* runs in $O(\log \log n)$ amortized time and other operations have optimal amortized bounds, but no tight $\Theta (\log \log n)$ bound is known for the original data structure.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Although the asymptotic performance of pairing heaps is worse than other priority queue algorithms such as Fibonacci heaps, which perform *decrease-key* in $O(1)$ amortized time, the performance in practice is excellent.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Jones and Larkin, Sen, and Tarjan conducted experiments on pairing heaps and other heap data structures.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] A pairing heap is either an empty heap, or a pairing tree consisting of a root element and a possibly empty list of pairing trees.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The heap ordering property requires that parent of any node is no greater than the node itself.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The following description assumes a purely functional heap that does not support the *decrease-key* operation.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] It can also be viewed as a variant of a Left-child right-sibling binary tree with an additional pointer to a node's parent (which represents its previous sibling or actual parent for the leftmost sibling).
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Alternatively, the previous-pointer can be omitted by letting the last child point back to the parent, if a single Boolean flag is added to indicate "end of list".
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] This achieves a more compact structure at the expense of a constant overhead factor per operation.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The only non-trivial fundamental operation is the deletion of the minimum element from the heap.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] This requires performing repeated melds of its children until only one tree remains.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:skew-heap/pairing-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:skew-heap/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] A **skew heap** (or **self-adjusting heap**) is a heap data structure implemented as a binary tree.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] Skew heaps are advantageous because of their ability to merge more quickly than binary heaps.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] In contrast with binary heaps, there are no structural constraints, so there is no guarantee that the height of the tree is logarithmic.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] A skew heap is a self-adjusting form of a leftist heap which attempts to maintain balance by unconditionally swapping all nodes in the merge path when merging two heaps.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] (The merge operation is also used when adding and removing values.) With no structural constraints, it may seem that a skew heap would be horribly inefficient.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] However, amortized complexity analysis can be used to demonstrate that all operations on a skew heap can be done in O(log *n*).
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] In fact, with ${\textstyle \varphi ={\frac {1+{\sqrt {5}}}{2}}}$ denoting the golden ratio, the exact amortized complexity is known to be logφ *n* (approximately 1.44 log2 *n*).
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] Alternatively, there is a non-recursive approach which is more wordy, and does require some sorting at the outset.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] Adding a value to a skew heap is like merging a tree with one node together with the original tree.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] Removing the first value in a heap can be accomplished by removing the root and merging its child subtrees.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] In many functional languages, skew heaps become extremely simple to implement.
[src:skew-heap/skew-heap] Here is a complete sample implementation in Haskell.
